<br>
I think VI grasped this fact a long time ago.  Giving mobs better AI is like throwing money into a bottomless pit.  With each improvement, there are new side effects that you don't intend, new loopholes that players can exploit, new bugs that you have to fix.  To spend that kind of resource to track down each bug, fix each loophole, while at the same time making the mobs smart is just not cost efficient - and that's what this business is all about.  Players have demonstrated that they are unwilling to pay $40 a month for a game, because realistically most people play this game as a form of enjoyment, not as their only hobby.  But if you're unwilling to pay $40 a month, then what makes you think VI is willing to spend millions hiring AI programmers? It's SO much easier to just make the mobs hit like trucks and AE rampage for 3k damage.  SO much easier to just script an encounter to spawn a ton of mobs, and leave it to you to figure out how to fight them rather than trying to plan out the mob's strategies and AI's.<br>
<br>
Does that mean better AI isn't a good direction for EQ to move in? No - frankly, I think the caster AI in EQ could use alot of work still.  But there are limits to the effects AI could have on the game, folks.  It's not the panacea of CRPGs as so many gamers have claimed over the years.  I mean, you'd think that if AI was as important as it was (and is) made out to be by just about everyone, the best gaming company would be the one that produced the best AI's.  Clearly that is not true.  Blizzard isn't known for their excellent AI's, but for their great gameplay and graphics.  Squaresoft isn't known for their excellent AI's, but for their epic graphic novelisque RPGs. VI isn't known for their excellent AI's, but for their addictive timesinks.  <br>
<br>
The list goes on.<br>
<br>
There is a reason why AI is so atrocious in most games these days, and it's not that game companies are too dumb to realize that gamers want it.<br>
